	   <tr><td colspan=2>***<br>Instead, it was meant to point out that with expanded skills, your chances of improving your weapons and thus improving your abilities improves as well.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>***<br><br>See, this is where I disagree.  Sure, expanding skills is important.  But it must be logical.  It's like if you want to make armor you take up smithing, right?  Makes sense, right?  So what if VI decides tommorow to come out with a new super armor made out of clay and only super master potters can make it?  See, that just doesn't make sense.  My point is that I won't sacrifice hours and hours of what I feel is the fun part of the game (adventuring at the limits of your character) to learn every odd skill in the event that VI just might make it the next big thing.  <br><br>Now, if there had been hints all along that blunt weapons might be a better or even equal choice then I could see the utility in learning these skills.  But the inability of certain classes to wield edged weapons has always been seen as a weakness.  How many clerics would wield blunts if they could used edged?  <br><br>Now on the other hand, pallys out there not keeping 2hs up and only using 1hs, should feel the sting of that at some point.  *That* makes sense.  But a blunt weapon?  You're not rewarding or punishing anyone.  You're just frustrating the players that now have to start back at the bottom for no good reason.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
